  "tips": [
    {
      "type": "lead",
      "text": "Your fingers now know every letter on the board. Today is not about new keys, it is about flow - typing short words on a steady beat until they feel automatic. Flow, not force."
    },
    {
      "type": "drop",
      "text": "Eyes up, hands on home row. Repeat each word at one even pace - same gap between every tap. Don't sprint, just hold the rhythm like a track playing on loop."
    },
    {
      "type": "callout",
      "icon": "🎶",
      "title": "Even beat",
      "text": "Find a tempo you can actually keep and lock in. Steady always beats rushed - smooth and even, not jerky and fast. Let the beat do the work for you."
    },
    {
      "type": "step",
      "kind": "drill",
      "target": "the the the the the",
      "finger": "blue",
      "title": "Rhythm: the",
      "hint": "Loop it on a steady beat: the - the - the. Same gap every time."
    },
    {
      "type": "step",
      "kind": "drill",
      "target": "fox fox fox fox",
      "finger": "blue",
      "title": "Rhythm: fox",
      "hint": "Hold the tempo: fox - fox - fox. Flow, not force."
    },
    {
      "type": "step",
      "kind": "drill",
      "target": "dog dog dog dog",
      "finger": "green",
      "title": "Rhythm: dog",
      "hint": "Keep it even to the end: dog - dog - dog. No speeding up."
    },
    {
      "type": "p",
      "text": "Notice how your hands start reaching for the whole word at once. That is the point - repetition on an even beat turns thinking into reflex, and reflex is where real speed comes from."
    },
    {
